{"type":"assistant","message":{"model":"claude-sonnet-4-6","id":"msg_01MzaYPZq3H3vKxLgHM7Qk4b","type":"message","role":"assistant","content":[{"type":"thinking","thinking":"There's no openssl-toolbox pod running yet. I need to create one. I'll deploy a temporary pod with openssl available to generate the certificates. Let me plan the full TLS migration:\n\n1. Create an openssl-toolbox pod in the cockroachdb namespace\n2. Generate certificates using the `cockroach cert` command (which is actually available in the cockroachdb containers themselves)\n3. Create Kubernetes secrets for the CA cert, node cert, and client cert\n4. Update the StatefulSet to use TLS (remove `--insecure`, add `--certs-dir`, mount certs, update probes to HTTPS)\n5. Roll the cluster\n\nI realize I can leverage the existing CockroachDB pods themselves to generate the certificates using their built-in `cockroach cert` command rather than spinning up a separate toolbox. The process involves creating a CA certificate first, then node certificates for each pod's DNS names, followed by a client certificate for the root user. Once I have all the certificates, I'll package them into Kubernetes secrets, mount them as volumes in the StatefulSet, switch from `--insecure` to `--certs-dir`, update the health checks to use HTTPS, and finally roll out the pods to apply the changes. the cockroach binary on crdb-cluster-0 to generate the certificates. The node cert needs to cover all the DNS names for each pod in the cluster, plus the public service endpoint, localhost, and the loopback IP. I'll generate the CA cert first, then the node cert with all those DNS names, then a client cert for root, and save them all as Kubernetes secrets.\n\nThe most straightforward approach is to create a single shared node certificate that includes all the pod DNS names as Subject Alternative Names rather than creating separate certs per pod. For CockroachDB, I need to follow the standard pattern of having one CA cert, one node cert covering all nodes, and one client cert for the root user.\n\nI'm listing out all the DNS names that need to be included in the node cert—the individual pod headless service names, the cluster service names, and localhost entries—then I'll use the cockroach binary running on the first pod to generate these certificates.","signature":""}],"stop_reason":null,"stop_sequence":null,"stop_details":null,"usage":{"input_tokens":1,"cache_creation_input_tokens":581,"cache_read_input_tokens":32349,"cache_creation":{"ephemeral_5m_input_tokens":0,"ephemeral_1h_input_tokens":581},"output_tokens":29,"service_tier":"standard","inference_geo":"not_available"},"diagnostics":null,"context_management":null},"parent_tool_use_id":null,"session_id":"ab62093c-ef76-453f-83cd-84d3752ec3fa","uuid":"b449c1d1-8f9b-4031-85a1-f9f80566dcb3","request_id":"req_011Cc5EEEcQEj5j5nMC55Swb"}
