{"type":"assistant","message":{"model":"claude-sonnet-4-6","id":"msg_01RfYxpsczTMQ8vvREwFGwZh","type":"message","role":"assistant","content":[{"type":"thinking","thinking":"Now I need to update the StatefulSet to:\n1. Remove `--insecure` flag from the command\n2. Add `--certs-dir=/cockroach/cockroach-certs`\n3. Mount the node cert secret as `/cockroach/cockroach-certs`\n4. Update the liveness probe from HTTP to HTTPS (or just port check)\n5. Update the readiness probe from HTTP to HTTPS\n\nThe current command is:\n```\nexec /cockroach/cockroach start --logtostderr=INFO --insecure --advertise-host=$(POD_NAME).crdb-cluster.cockroachdb.svc.cluster.local --http-addr=0.0.0.0:8080 --port=26257 --cache=25% --max-sql-memory=25% --join=crdb-cluster-0.crdb-cluster.cockroachdb.svc.cluster.local:26257,\n```\n\nI need to change it to:\n```\nexec /cockroach/cockroach start --logtostderr=INFO --certs-dir=/cockroach/cockroach-certs --advertise-host=$(POD_NAME).crdb-cluster.cockroachdb.svc.cluster.local --http-addr=0.0.0.0:8080 --port=26257 --cache=25% --max-sql-memory=25% --join=crdb-cluster-0.cr\n```\n\nUpdating the startup command...\n\nNow I'm thinking about the health probes since HTTPS will be required on port 8080 in secure mode. I could either switch the liveness probe to use HTTPS or use exec-based probes instead. Let me verify whether CockroachDB's secure mode runs HTTP or HTTPS on port 8080 for the admin UI.\n\nIn secure mode, the admin UI serves over HTTPS by default, so the current HTTP probes will fail. I can update the probes to use `scheme: HTTPS` and the kubelet will handle the certificate verification, or I could use an exec probe with the `cockroach node status` command instead.\n\nFor the StatefulSet patch, I need to remove the `--insecure` flag, add `--certs-dir` pointing to the mounted certificates, and update the liveness and readiness probes to use HTTPS. I also need to mount the cockroachdb-node-certs secret as a volume and set the correct file permissions—CockroachDB requires the node.key to be readable only by the cockroach process (mode 0600), so I'll use `defaultMode` on the secret volume to restrict access appropriately.\n\nHowever, there's a critical issue with the rolling update: CockroachDB doesn't support mixed secure and insecure modes in a cluster. When pods restart with TLS enabled, they'll try to connect to nodes still running in insecure mode, which will fail. The proper approach is to stop all nodes first, update their configuration with certificates, then restart them together so the entire cluster transitions to secure mode at once.\n\nFor a dev environment, I can scale the StatefulSet down to zero replicas, update the pod spec with the new command and volume mounts, then scale back up. Since the data persists on PVCs, nothing will be lost, and all nodes will come up in secure mode simultaneously.\n\nBut wait—I notice the StatefulSet has `podManagementPolicy: Parallel`, which means if I patch the spec and then delete all pods at once, they'll all restart in parallel rather than rolling one by one. That's actually perfect for this scenario since a rolling update would fail when the first TLS-enabled pod tries to connect to insecure peers.\n\nHowever, there's a critical constraint I need to check: CockroachDB stores cluster state in its data directory, and switching from insecure to secure mode isn't straightforward. The older documentation said you can't migrate without data loss, but I should verify if there's a proper migration path in the newer versions that allows enabling TLS while preserving data.\n\nFor this test scenario, the most practical approach would be to patch the StatefulSet with the certificate volumes and mounts, then update the startup command to remove the `--insecure` flag. Since the pods use parallel management, they'll all restart simultaneously with TLS enabled. But I need to confirm whether CockroachDB v24.1 supports this kind of in-place migration or if we need to handle the data directory differently. add `--certs-dir`, and add the volume mount for certificates. The rolling restart should bring the cluster up in secure mode. For the data persistence issue, since this is a test environment, I can either wipe the PVCs or attempt the switch directly and see if it works. Let me go with the practical approach and patch the StatefulSet first.\n\nI also need to update the liveness and readiness probes to use HTTPS since the admin UI will be serving on HTTPS in secure mode. And I should set the certificate file permissions correctly with `defaultMode: 0640` on the secret volume.\n\nCreating the patch...","signature":""}],"stop_reason":null,"stop_sequence":null,"stop_details":null,"usage":{"input_tokens":1,"cache_creation_input_tokens":404,"cache_read_input_tokens":36424,"cache_creation":{"ephemeral_5m_input_tokens":0,"ephemeral_1h_input_tokens":404},"output_tokens":28,"service_tier":"standard","inference_geo":"not_available"},"diagnostics":null,"context_management":null},"parent_tool_use_id":null,"session_id":"ab62093c-ef76-453f-83cd-84d3752ec3fa","uuid":"df747505-8d10-44b6-9245-31d3d0db3d8c","request_id":"req_011Cc5EHtpe4JXdL4PZJ8SH3"}
